<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: TUSTIN; TUBERCULOSIS TESTING KEPT CLINICS BUSY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALAN EYERLY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 New regulations on testing for tuberculosis bacteria helped make 
back-to-school immunization clinics busier than usual at Tustin Unified School 
District. 
</P>
<P>
 Free clinics for school-age children and preschoolers were held Monday and 
last Wednesday, the day before classes started. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've never been so crowded," said Margo Stone, nurse coordinator for the 
school district. All first-grade students and any students new to Orange County 
schools were required to show proof of receiving a tuberculosis skin test 
within the last 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
 The new regulations, she said, have "really increased attendance at our 
clinics." 
</P>
<P>
 There are about 13,000 students enrolled in the Tustin district, which serves 
preschoolers through high school seniors. 
</P>
<P>
 Besides offering tuberculosis testing, the district immunizes children against 
diphtheria, tetanus, whooping cough, polio, measles, mumps and rubella. 
</P>
<P>
 From October through June, the school district will offer free immunization 
clinics to Tustin area residents of all ages. This expanded program will be 
held in conjunction with the Orange County Health Care Agency. 
</P>
<P>
 The clinics will generally be conducted from 1 to 3:30 p.m. on the second 
Monday of the month at Guin Foss School, a district resource center at 18492 
Vanderlip Ave. 
</P>
<P>
 For more information on the clinics, call the district at (714) 730-7322.ALAN 
EYERLY 
</P>
