<HEADLINE>
<P>
OCPS WILL APPEAL LOWER STATE GRANT; FUNDING: ARTS COUNCIL CONCERN ABOUT 
SALARIES, DIVERSITY ARE MISPLACED, DIRECTOR SAYS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS PASLES, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Orange County Philharmonic Society will appeal the state arts council's 
decision to reduce the society's 1994-95 grant by more than one-third, society 
director Dean Corey said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 A council program manager said last week that the grant was lowered to $20,687 
from $33,005 last year because the California Arts Council is concerned that 
the society's administrative salaries are increasing while the salaries it pays 
artists are declining.Further concerns, the program manager said, were a lack 
of cultural diversity among the group's board members, and what the council 
considers insufficient board involvement in outreach programs. 
</P>
<P>
 Corey said Monday that the administrative "salaries probably went up a little, 
but not significantly." 
</P>
<P>
 On the grant application, he said, "I consolidated all the salaries, which 
makes it look like they took a big leap. Previously, they had been scattered 
around -- in the marketing budget, the development budget, the administrative 
budget and the education budget. . . . Evidently, we didn't footnote that 
properly. 
</P>
<P>
 "On the other issues, we don't have enough of a diverse representation on 
board membership, but we certainly are diverse in the people we serve, probably 
more than any other Orange County arts group." 
</P>
<P>
 Corey said he will file the appeal after he receives the arts council's 
written notification of its action, in about three weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091394-0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 078845 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
